(a) As with vowels (§ 20), it is desirable to substitute more
familiar consonant letters for less familiar ones, when such a sub
stitution can be made without causing ambiguity. For instance,
in a language containing a retroflex J; but no dental t the sound
could generally be denoted by t. And in a language such as
